{"questionId":"11732","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The curve&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"y = f\\left( x \\right)\">\n  <mi>y</mi>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mi>f</mi>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mi>x</mi>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>&nbsp;is shown in the graph, for&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"0 \\leqslant x \\leqslant 10\">\n  <mn>0</mn>\n  <mo>⩽</mo>\n  <mi>x</mi>\n  <mo>⩽</mo>\n  <mn>10</mn>\n</math></span>.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/0a44fa05389ed914ed86a1ea66c71882666a4a36.png\"></p>\n<p>The curve&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"y = f\\left( x \\right)\">\n  <mi>y</mi>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mi>f</mi>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mi>x</mi>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>&nbsp;passes through the following points.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/adf9974b6e26c279a59fd52f8b99005acb9af1e3.png\"></p>\n<p>It is required to find the area bounded by the curve, the <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x\">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n</math></span><em>-</em>axis, the <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"y\">\n  <mi>y</mi>\n</math></span><em>-</em>axis and the line <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x = 10\">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mn>10</mn>\n</math></span>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>One possible model for the curve&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"y = f\\left( x \\right)\">\n  <mi>y</mi>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mi>f</mi>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mi>x</mi>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>&nbsp;is a cubic function.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Use all the coordinates in the table to find the equation of the least squares cubic regression curve.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"y = 0.0389{x^3} - 0.534{x^2} + 2.06x + 2.06\">\n  <mi>y</mi>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mn>0.0389</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msup>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>3</mn>\n    </msup>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>−</mo>\n  <mn>0.534</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msup>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n    </msup>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>2.06</mn>\n  <mi>x</mi>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>2.06</mn>\n</math></span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>M1A2</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"11732","referenceCode":"EXM.2.AHL.TZ0.12b.i","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Use all the coordinates in the table to find the equation of the least squares cubic regression curve.","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b.i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 5—Calculus","Topic 5—Calculus","SL 5.8—Trapezoid rule","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","AHL 4.13—Non-linear regression"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}